◊indented-justified{If we look at government agencies around us that stand out as ‘best,’ we will find they consist of cohesive groups of women and men who are ‘turned on’ by something. But by what? Not their paychecks, nor the latest reform gimmicks, but by the very work they are doing: stopping child abuse, fighting forest fires, battling epidemics.}
◊sig{—Charles Goodsell, ◊book{Mission Mystique}*}

◊aside{*Credit for introducing me to this quote goes to ◊link["https://danhonig.info" "Dan Honig,"] who also features it on his website. It captures the human element of governance that has long motivated my work.}
I am a first-year Ph.D. student and Ashford Fellow in Government and Social Policy at ◊link["https://www.gov.harvard.edu/people/graduate-students/" "Harvard University,"] and an affiliate of the ◊link["https://caps.gov.harvard.edu/" "Center for American Political Studies."] My research examines how legal regimes build, reshape, and constrain American political institutions—particularly the federal bureaucracy and Congress. 

I came to graduate study by way of law, after working in various roles across the federal government: in the executive branch, on Capitol Hill, and in the federal judiciary. Those experiences drew me to questions about how institutions actually work. Much of what institutions do—and how well they do it—turns on things legal categories do not always capture: the motivations and limitations of the people inside them, the organizational cultures that form around them, and the informal practices through which formal authority is exercised. My work sits within the American Political Development tradition, combining insights from administrative law and organizational theory with historical-institutional methods to study how the American administrative state has been built, contested, and reshaped over the long run.

Outside of research, I enjoy yoga, drinking more coffee than I should, and spending plenty of time at bookstores. I also care a lot about typography and design—this site being one small outlet for that (see the ◊xref["colophon.html" "colophon"])—and am an avid follower of consumer technology.